<h1>TRIGGER</h1>

<p>
Trigger is the point where internal stability stops functioning in its baseline state and shifts into instinct-driven processing. It is not a reaction itself, but the transition phase where the system begins reorganizing in response to disruption.
</p>

<p>
Trigger can originate from social interaction or environmental conditions. Social triggers include conflict, disagreement, miscommunication, tension in tone, interruption, or any shift in communication that disrupts expected flow or creates instability in interaction.
</p>

<p>
Environmental triggers include changes in routine, loss of structure, unpredictable outcomes, shifts in surroundings, emotional pressure accumulation, or situations that stop following expected patterns or continuity.
</p>

<p>
When trigger occurs, the system does not immediately produce a conscious response. Internal processing shifts into evaluation and reorganization, scanning for stability, direction, and control while adapting to the disruption.
</p>

<p>
Once this threshold is crossed, neutrality is no longer maintained. The system transitions into one of the animal response patterns depending on internal structure, and perception is filtered through that activated state.
</p>

